Fr&lt;U+00E4&gt;ngsmyr et al. (1983), p. 170.
Fr&lt;U+00E4&gt;ngsmyr et al. (1983), p. 167, quotes Linnaeus explaining the real difference would necessarily be absent from his classification system, as it was not a morphological characteristic: ''&quot;I well know what a splendidly great difference there is [between] a man and a bestia [literally, &quot;beast&quot;; that is, a non-human animal] when I look at them from a point of view of morality. Man is the animal which the Creator has seen fit to honor with such a magnificent mind and has condescended to adopt as his favorite and for which he has prepared a nobler life&quot;''. See also books.google.com in which Linnaeus cites the significant capacity to reason as the distinguishing characteristic of humans.
